sec.p:
The performance evaluation tests on the cyclone were conducted using the 35 kg/h biomass gasifier system installed at Siemens Renewable Energy Innovation Center, Bangalore, India. The collection efficiency of the originally fitted cyclone was found to vary between 21% and 25% at the rated throughput. As the performance of cyclone was a long way below generally acceptable performance, it was decided to examine the reasons behind poor collection efficiency and use the findings to design a new cyclone of higher efficiency. Therefore, one of the objectives of this study was to design a new cyclone with improved collection efficiency at a minimum acceptable pressure drop. Furthermore, the new cyclone was expected to reduce the dust loading on the subsequent gas cleaning systems. The specific objectives of the study are given as:


to examine the reasons for poor collection efficiency of the original cyclone and compare the experimental results against the estimated results using theoretical models;

to identify the critical geometrical parameters that influence the cyclone performance;

make use of the findings from (a) and (b) to design a new cyclone for improved performance; and

to employ computational tools such as CFD for performance evaluation of the cyclone.

The aim of the literature survey was multifold and is as follows:


to have best practice advice for modeling cyclone separators based on the previous published work;

identify appropriate mesh type and mesh resolution for accuracy;

identify appropriate flow models (turbulence, multiphase, etc.);

identify appropriate computational domain and corresponding boundary conditions; and

validate the envisaged simulation approach and solver settings against the work in the published literature.
